Here's how to implement all three:

**1 & 2 — Guard navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation from EditProductPage
    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

Key points:
- `GetDeferral()` is **required** for async checks — without it the navigation completes before your `await` finishes.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user taps "Stay".
- Call `deferral.Complete()` in **all** paths (discard or stay).

**3 — Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage"
             Title="Edit Product">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

In your ViewModel (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers a Pop, which hits the OnNavigating guard above
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` **replaces** the default back action, so you must call `GoToAsync("..")` yourself. That pop is then intercepted by `OnNavigating`, giving you the confirmation dialog on both the custom button and the system back gesture.
